'''Simon Adingra''' (born 1 January 2002) is an Ivorian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Ligue 1]] club [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]], on loan from [[Premier League]] club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], and the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast national team]].<ref name="soccerway">{{Soccerway|688732}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Adingra was born in [[Abobo]], a suburb of [[Abidjan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4353211 |title=Sunderland sign winger Adingra from Brighton |publisher=Premier League |date=10 July 2025 |access-date=11 July 2025}}</ref> A former player of the [[Right to Dream Academy]], Adingra joined Danish club [[FC Nordsjælland|Nordsjælland]] in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=FRA AKADEMI TIL SUPERLIGA: SIMON ADINGRA|url=https://fcn.dk/2021/01/fra-akademi-til-superliga-simon-adingra/|date=28 January 2021|access-date=1 August 2021}}</ref> He made his professional debut on 18 April 2021 in a 2–2 league draw against [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]]. He replaced [[Ivan Mesík]] at the 68th minute of the game and went on to score his team's second goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=SIMON SCOREDE I SIN DRØMMEDEBUT: JEG ER KLAR PÅ AT GRIBE MIN CHANCE|work=FC Nordsjælland |url=https://fcn.dk/2021/04/simon-scorede-i-sin-droemmedebut-jeg-er-klar-paa-at-gribe-min-chance/|date=19 April 2021|access-date=1 August 2021 |last1=Carlsson |first1=Mads }}</ref>

===Brighton and Hove Albion===
On 24 June 2022, Adingra transferred to [[Premier League]] club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], signing a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2654932/simon-adingra-signs-for-albion|title=Simon Adingra signs for Albion|date=24 June 2022|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|access-date=24 June 2022}}</ref> Ten days later, Adingra joined Brighton's Belgian sister club [[Royale Union Saint-Gilloise|Union SG]] on loan for the [[2022–23 Royale Union Saint-Gilloise season|2022–23 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2658490/simon-adingra-joins-royale-union-saint-gilloise-on-loan|title= Simon Adingra joins Royale Union Saint-Gilloise on loan|date=4 July 2022|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|access-date=5 July 2022}}</ref>

Adingra made his Brighton debut as a substitute in the opening game of the [[2023–24 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2023–24 season]] on 12 August. He scored the Seagulls' third goal in an eventual 4–1 home win over newly promoted [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/3630184/subs-seal-impressive-win-for-albion|title=Subs seal impressive win for Albion|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion|date=12 August 2023|access-date=12 August 2023}}</ref> During that same season, Adingra made his first Premier League start on 16 September in a 3–1 victory over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in which he recorded an assist.<ref>{{Cite web|date=16 September 2023|title=Shambolic Manchester United endure crowd dissent after humbling defeat to Brighton|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/manchester-united-brighton-premier-league-result-b2412820.html|access-date=27 October 2023|website=The Independent|language=en}}</ref>

Upon returning to Brighton after winning the 2023 AFCON title, Adingra would score a brace in a 5–0 win against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on 18 February 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rindl |first=Joe |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68266300 |title=Sheffield United 0–5 Brighton: Mason Holgate sent off in heavy home defeat|website=BBC Sport|date=18 February 2024|access-date=11 July 2025}}</ref>

===Sunderland===
On 10 July 2025, Adingra joined fellow Premier League club [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], signing a five-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.safc.com/news/2025/july/10/adingra-arrives-from-brighton/|title=Adingra arrives from Brighton|date=10 July 2025|publisher=Sunderland A.F.C.|access-date=10 July 2025}}</ref> On 28 December 2025, he scored his first goal for the club in a 1–1 draw at home against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cgex3ln0yj0o|title=Sunderland analysis: Missed chances rued in draw against Leeds|date=28 December 2025|publisher=BBC.com|access-date=28 December 2025}}</ref>

=== Loan to Monaco ===
On 2 February 2026, Sunderland announced that Adingra had been loaned to [[AS Monaco FC|AS Monaco]] for the rest of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Adingra joins AS Monaco on loan |url=https://www.safc.com/news/2026/february/02/adingra-joins-/ |access-date=2026-02-02 |website=www.safc.com}}</ref>

==International career==
In March 2023, Adingra received his first call-up to the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast senior national team]] for two [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group H|Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] matches against [[Comoros national football team|Comoros]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 March 2023 |title=Elim. CAN 2023 (3è et 4è CIV-COM & COM-CIV) : Jean Louis Gasset dévoile les 23 Eléphants |url=http://www.fifciv.com/?q=elim-can-2023-3%C3%A8-et-4%C3%A8-civ-com-com-civ-jean-louis-gasset-d%C3%A9voile-les-23-el%C3%A9phants |access-date=17 March 2023 |website=Fédération Ivoirienne de Football}}</ref>

On 3 February 2024, Adingra scored a 90th minute equaliser in an eventual extra-time 2–1 win against [[Mali national football team|Mali]] in the quarter-finals of [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web |date= 3 February 2024|title=Match Centre |url=https://www.cafonline.com/caf-africa-cup-of-nations/match-centre?competition=190&season=2023&match=2414316 |access-date=3 February 2024|website= Confédération Africaine de Football}}</ref> On 11 February, he provided two assists and was named as man of the match in the tournament's [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations final|final]] against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], which ended in a 2–1 victory for Ivory Coast.<ref name="2023caff">{{cite web |date=11 February 2024 |title=Nigeria 1–2 Ivory Coast: Sebastian Haller grabs winner as Hosts win Africa Cup of Nations after Wild Tournament |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/africa-cup-of-nations/2024/nigeria-v-ivory-coast-afcon-final-live_sto10013363/story.shtml |access-date=11 February 2024 |publisher=Eurosport}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Stevens |first=Rob |date=11 February 2024 |title=Nigeria 1–2 Ivory Coast |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68196261 |access-date=14 February 2024 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On May 15, 2026, Adingra was integrated by Ivory Coast coach [[Emerse Faé]] in his list of 26 players in order to participate in the [[2026 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|access-date=2 June 2026 |date=15 May 2026 |language=fr |title=La liste de la Côte d'Ivoire pour la Coupe du Monde 2026 |url=https://www.fifa.com/fr/articles/liste-cote-d-ivoire-coupe-du-monde-2026 |website=[[FIFA]]}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator --></ref>

